Sub-Saharan African Stocks: AccessKenya, Pan African Insurance

-- B y   E r i c   O m b o k
-- 
2011-03-16T14:40:30Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-16/sub-saharan-african-stocks-accesskenya-pan-african-insurance.html
Mauritius’s SEMDEX Index retreated
for a fourth day, losing 0.8 percent to 1,979.27 by the 1:30
p.m. close in  Port Louis .    Kenya ’s All-Share Index rallied 0.5 percent to 74.34 by the
3 p.m. close in Nairobi, a fourth day of increases. The Nigerian
Stock Exchange All-Share Index dropped 1 percent to 24,890.42 by
2:45 p.m. in Lagos, according to data compiled by Bloomberg.
Namibia’s FTSE  Namibia Overall Index (FTN098)  snapped two days of
declines, rising 0.7 percent to 831.52 by 3:56 p.m. in Windhoek.
The Ghana Stock Exchange Composite Index increased 0.2 percent
to 1,068.48, a third day of advances.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan  Africa ,
excluding  South Africa . Stock symbols are in parentheses.    AccessKenya (ACCESS)  Group Ltd. (ACCESS KN), the country’s only
publicly traded Internet company, rose to the highest level this
month, climbing 30 cents, or 3.2 percent to 9.7 shillings,
paring its year-to-date decline to 28 percent. The stock is the
market’s worst performer this year.  “They got punished enough by the market, they have had a
massive depreciation,” Timothy Wambu, a research analyst at
Nairobi-based CFC Stanbic Financial Services, said in a phone
interview today. “People are coming back because the price is
now at an attractive entry level.”    Pan Africa Insurance Holdings Ltd. (PAIL)  , the Kenyan
unit of South Africa-based Sanlam Ltd., rallied the most in 4
1/2 years, gaining 19 shillings, or 24 percent, to 98.5
shillings. Net income quadrupled to 589.3 million shillings
($6.87 million) in the 12 months through December, the Nairobi-
based company said in a statement distributed by the city’s
stock exchange yesterday. Sanlam is South Africa’s largest
insurer.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Eric Ombok in Nairobi at 
